June 2020

Context

Prediktor is a Shiny app which has been developed in the scope of the capstone project of the Data Science Specialization offered by John Hopkins University and available on coursera.
The specialization contains 10 courses which cover an in-depth introduction to data science, via R programming. In particular, courses cover:

  • Statisitcal Inference and Regression Models
  • Practical Machine Learning
  • Natural Language Processing (via the capstone project).

The capstone project, that is to say the app, is here to showcase the skills acquired during the specialization.
The app is available here: Prediktor

How it works

Prediktor tries to predict the next word in a sentence you type as input. For instance, if you type

bag of

it will return

  [1] "chips"    "money"    "skittles"

It’s as simple as that. Try it out yourself!

The magic behind the scenes

The prediction model was built using tweets, blogs posts and news articles provided by Swiftkey, based on n-grams.
As for any other app, some choices have been made, in particular choices regarding the accuracy vs. the performance. With this in mind, only 2-grams and 3-grams have been used, built on a random (yet hopefully representative) sample of texts.

Additionally, it is to be noted the vocabulary of the input texts being not particularly rich (tweets and blog posts aren’t renown for that), elaborated sentences may not produce the best prediction results.

If you want to find out more about how the app was built, reach out to me.
